{"at": "2026-06-05T01:44:34Z", "commit_ref": "none", "intent": "feature-list", "actor": "user", "kind": "input", "content": "We are going to work on Optical Constructor UI. I will give you some sketches and your task is to analyze current code and specs, look up the web for similar apps, check the ideas, and then expand that text below into a feature list. The list below is incomplete, so do your best.\n\nCurrent main screen becomes the “legacy” form available via the legacy menu item. It is a good illustration of what’s available.\n\nThe main screen layout. I think that Word / Excel have a very good layout structure: top menu switches the ribbons, the ribbons provide controls of what is relevant to the current task. But, if the ribbon is hidden, then the menu becomes a fully expanded menu, which allows doing everything that the ribbons allow. \n\nHere are some general comments\n\nLanguages EN / RU (saved into settings). Both must be supported. All pairs of strings must be in some centralized place for ease of maintenance. JSON, YAML, or something like that file, which will be consumed at run time AND can be edited to change the strings / add languages. The system must check that nothing is missing and default to some English text and show the error message at startup, which would allow the user to copy it.\nUnits of measure – m, cm, mm, mkm, nm, A, and in in case somebody wants them. A lot was written about them in previous specs. There are no changes here.\nStandardize controls – single place to describe. If a new flavor of controls is needed (e.g. a button of different color), then it is added there and changes to the least of properties that are needed to make the control stand out are made.\nCheck all the proposed buttons / mouse actions below, advise if that could be improved.\nDCLK – opens element dialog.\nRIGHT CLICK – menu: element dialog, local help, ???.\nCTRL+Z – undo. More than one level is needed.\nCTRL+Y – redo\nSHIFT+R (with confirmation) – resets the element to its standard rotation (R1 = 0, R2 = 0, R3 = 0).\nF1 – local help – show help about selected object (what the controls do) – a pop up window.\nESC – close local menu.\nActive element must be shown so that it is clear that it is an active element. All actions happen ONLY with the chosen (active) element.\nCome up with some other hotkeys if they make sense.\n\nActive element – that’s the element that is currently selected.\nElement – 3 angles of rotation: rotation around primary normal to the element (R1 – this needs clarification if the light ray is a horizontal line from the left to the right, then R1 is a rotation around that line), rotation around normal to the table (R2), rotation around R1 x R2 (R3, very rarely used, must be unlocked first).\nMOUSE LEFT PRESS + MOVE on element DOES NOT DO anything because it is very easy to do.\nSHIFT + MOUSE LEFT PRESS + MOVE – moves PP (see below) along CR. See the OT for its specifics.\nSHIFT + MOUSE WHEEL –R1, step 5 degrees (in config), if not locked, \nCTRL + MOUSE WHEEL –R2, step 5 degrees (in config), if not locked\nALT + MOUSE WHEEL – R3 (must be unlocked first), step 5 degrees (in config)\nEach element must show the value of R1, R2, R3 nearby, clicking on that must allow editing the values by hand (and have a reset button for each of all rotations). R3 is locked by default. The user may lock / unlock any of the rotations (with the current values) to prevent changes.\n\nOptical Table (OT) – the place where all the editing happens. Default view is from the top and in most of the cases this is all that we need. The table is selected when the user clicks on anything that is NOT an optical element (see below).\nMouse LEFT PRESS + MOVE – moves the table with all elements on it.\nMouse wheel - zoom in / out.\nRotations of the table just changes the view and so all elements “travel” with the table. R1, R2, R3 for the table are relative to the screen. There must be an easy way to reset the view to (0, 0, 0).\n\nOptical Element (OE) – the basic unit in the optical constructor.\nThere are two special ones: light source (LS) and photo detector (PD), check the name. A light source draws three parallel lines: the central ray (CR) and 4 side rays, two left / right and two top / bottom (above CR and so coincide with CR when viewed from the top and when there are no element that will “unhide” them) (all together - the ray group, (RG)). The side rays are only important when lenses, non-flat mirrors, prisms / wedges, etc. are used. All elements except mirrors produce transmitted T and reflected R ray groups (TRG and RRG). Mirrors produce only RRG. This is only at the level of the metadata attached to the OE – any element can be configured to ignore R or T but not both. Mirrors are placed with T turned off, all other elements are places with whatever they are configured to turn off, if any. Turning off the second one automatically turns on the other one. The PD terminates the RG. The light falling on an element is called incident light (IRG). Any RG falling on the element is IRG from that element point of view. Each element has a placement point (PP). PP of each element snaps to CR or IRG. If some element is rotated in such a way that RG after the element changes the direction, then PP “travels” with the CR. All element rotations are ALWAYS measured in relation to IRG CR. So, if e.g. RRG changes direction due to some element rotation, then all the elements on the way change their place because the PP snaps in and then a rotation relative to IRG also snaps in.\n\nWe need to agree on how to trace the rays when any element is rotated so that R2 and or R3 are not null. The drawing on the table is a schema. So, we use standard n = 1 outside, n = 1.5 inside and then use Snell’s law to draw the lines.\n\nWe need to agree on the standard elements. These are the names on the table. For example, a light source could be a green laser OR a mercury lamp. This is still an LS on the optical table. Here are some proposed names\nOptical Table (OT)\nLight Source (LS)\nLinear Polarizer (LP)\nCircular Polarizer (CP)\nSample (S)\nPhoto Detector (PD) – but check the name\n\nExperiment collection – a set of experiments around the same material or materials, called sample / samples. The collection exists to make it convenient to easily “turn” on / off elements in the experiment.\n\nElement Group – one or more optical elements that we can easily place / remove on the way of the CR. There is always a primary CR path (but we can put in more PDs if really necessary). The groups are blocks on the way of the CR or CRs if we place multiple PDs. For example, here is a typical experiment:\nLS => Group 1 (Nothing or LP1 or CP1) => Group 2 (Nothing or S1 or S2 or S1 + S2) => Group 3 (Nothing or LP2 or CP2) => PD\nThe users should be able to quickly assemble the experiment out of chosen pieces. The experiment could be repeated because the conditions have changed.\n\nPD – if more than one, then the user must be able to choose the primary one."}
{"at": "2026-06-05T01:44:34Z", "commit_ref": "none", "intent": "spec", "actor": "agent", "kind": "decision", "content": "Authored .feature-list-md for the Optical Constructor UI: Office-style ribbon/menu shell with legacy form, EN/RU centralized editable strings with startup completeness check, standardized controls, optical table view/navigation, optical-element model (R1/R2/R3 rotations with per-axis lock and reset, active-element clarity), ray model (LS ray group, CR + side rays, RRG/TRG, mirror RRG-only, PD termination, PP snapping, n=1/n=1.5 Snell schematic), standard element catalogue, reviewed and extended mouse/keyboard scheme, element groups and experiment assembly, experiment collections, multi-level undo/redo, local help; flagged open questions (PD name, R1 axis, Ctrl+wheel-vs-zoom, ribbon tabs, schematic conventions).\n"}
{"at": "2026-06-05T01:53:09Z", "commit_ref": "none", "intent": "feature-list", "actor": "user", "kind": "escalation", "content": "out-of-scope: Temp/0026-feature-list-summary.txt (allowed: .feature-list-md, .history, .manual, .manual/*, .artifacts, .artifacts/*)"}
{"at": "2026-06-05T18:51:00Z", "commit_ref": "84cc050", "intent": "feature-list", "actor": "user", "kind": "input", "content": "Here are the comments and answers to open questions.\nAll elements are represented via their bounding box with two normals and a drawers. When the element is placed on the table without a rotation, then the first normal N1 is along CR ( and R1) and the second normal N2 is along R2. R1 always coincides with N1. Most, if not all elements will have bounding boxes the A x A x B type with N1 perpendicular to the square A x A. Optical elements are thin and wide AO > BO, light source is long BL > AL and narrow, AO > AL, BL > BO, Detector is like an optical element. The drawer is a function, which given the placement point and 3 rotations will draw the element. Let’s start from all elements being cylinders and one standard drawer that will draw all the elements as cylinder frame and very light gray transparent inside so that we can see the rays. The light source should have darker color, and the detector must be almost black but the frame must be still visible. The drawer must support an option to show / hide bounding box. This is convenient to visualize the rotations. The choice of R1, R2, R3 is dictated by the construction of optical fittings. As a result, if R3 is non-zero, then R1 is no longer perpendicular to R2. Optical table is a grey plate, by default 1.2 m x 2 m x 10 cm in the physical world, but the user may change the size.\n\nThe elements not just, e.g. LP, CP, S, but also have the underlying value, e.g. what kind of sample do we use. For the purposes of this spec we need to allocate the id in the schema so that the actual id of the element could be later bound to the element on the table and add a functionality on the element menu. At this point it should just open empty modal dialog.\n\nDetector name – used detector (D).\nR1 – this is rotation around a normal to the surface of the element. This coincides with the CR when there is a normal incidence. R2 is always a rotation around the normal to the optical table. If R2 != 0, then R1 axis is NOT the same as CR.\nCTRL +wheel. Let’s use CTRL +wheel as the standard zoom in / out and use CTRL + SHIFT + WHEEL for R2.\nRibbon tab set. Agree on the proposed set as a starting point.\nSide-ray and schematic conventions. Use a single CR and 8 side rays. If they hit a surface at normal incidence, then they will be equidistant dots on a circle (45 degrees between each) and CR will hit the center of that circle. There must be an option to show only CR or CR and all side rays. Lok up the web and work out the size / thicknesses of lines. There are tons of schematic pictures on the web and what is good visibility is well-known.\nThe polarizer is a polarizer no matter where it is placed. Also nothing prohibits to have more than two of them, after which the terminology gets blurred.\n\nWhere groups and collections live in storage. Let’s just store them in a separate JSON. The optical constructor is a complicated UI piece. I want it build first before doing anything else.\n\nUpdate the feature list."}
{"at": "2026-06-05T18:51:00Z", "commit_ref": "84cc050", "intent": "spec", "actor": "agent", "kind": "decision", "content": "Updated Optical Constructor feature list with operator answers: added element geometry (bounding box, N1/N2 normals, A x A x B proportions by role, standard cylinder drawer with light-grey transparent interior, darker source, near-black detector, show/hide bounding-box toggle); corrected R1 = rotation about surface normal (coincides with CR only at normal incidence, R2 != 0 decouples it), R2 about table normal, R3 third box axis with R3 != 0 breaking R1-perpendicular-R2 from optical-fitting mounts; settled Detector (D) naming and \"polarizer is a polarizer anywhere\" (no analyzer kind); 1 CR + 8 side rays on a 45-degree circle with show-CR-only/show-all toggle; Ctrl+wheel = zoom, Ctrl+Shift+wheel = R2; grey optical-table plate default 1.2 m x 2 m x 10 cm resizable; element id slot in schema plus placeholder element-menu action opening an empty modal; groups/collections in a separate JSON; ribbon tab set accepted; build the constructor first; trimmed resolved open questions to spec-author detail items.\n"}
{"at": "2026-06-05T18:58:10Z", "commit_ref": "84cc050", "intent": "feature-list", "actor": "user", "kind": "output", "content": "[tool Edit] {\"replace_all\": false, \"file_path\": \"C:\\\\GitHub\\\\Berreman\\\\specs\\\\0026\\\\.feature-list-md\", \"old_string\": \"**Photo detector terminates the ray.** A **photo detector (PD)**\\n**ter...\nNow §9 — catalogue: detector naming, the polarizer/analyzer resolution, and the new \"underlying value / id binding\" capability.\n[tool Edit] {\"replace_all\": false, \"file_path\": \"C:\\\\GitHub\\\\Berreman\\\\specs\\\\0026\\\\.feature-list-md\", \"old_string\": \"- **Optical Table (OT)** — the workspace itself.\\n- **Light Source (LS)...\nNow §10 — the Ctrl+wheel resolution. The operator made Ctrl+wheel the standard zoom and moved R2 to Ctrl+Shift+wheel.\n[tool Edit] {\"replace_all\": false, \"file_path\": \"C:\\\\GitHub\\\\Berreman\\\\specs\\\\0026\\\\.feature-list-md\", \"old_string\": \"- **Shift + mouse wheel** → R1, default step **5°** (configurable), if\\...\n[tool Grep] {\"pattern\": \"PD|[Pp]hoto [Dd]etector|photo detector\", \"path\": \"C:\\\\GitHub\\\\Berreman\\\\specs\\\\0026\\\\.feature-list-md\", \"output_mode\": \"content\", \"-n\": true}\n[tool Edit] {\"replace_all\": false, \"file_path\": \"C:\\\\GitHub\\\\Berreman\\\\specs\\\\0026\\\\.feature-list-md\", \"old_string\": \"- **Mouse wheel** (with no modifier) **zooms** in and out.\", \"new_strin...\n[tool Read] {\"file_path\": \"C:\\\\GitHub\\\\Berreman\\\\specs\\\\0026\\\\.feature-list-md\", \"offset\": 480, \"limit\": 25}\n[tool Edit] {\"replace_all\": false, \"file_path\": \"C:\\\\GitHub\\\\Berreman\\\\specs\\\\0026\\\\.feature-list-md\", \"old_string\": \"> LS ⇒ Group 1 (nothing, or LP1, or CP1) ⇒ Group 2 (nothing, or S1,\\n> ...\n[tool Edit] {\"replace_all\": false, \"file_path\": \"C:\\\\GitHub\\\\Berreman\\\\specs\\\\0026\\\\.feature-list-md\", \"old_string\": \"**Multiple detectors and the primary one.** The primary path normally\\n...\nNow update §1's pointer to the ribbon-tab question (now accepted as a starting point), then rewrite the Open Questions and Glossary sections.\n[tool Edit] {\"replace_all\": false, \"file_path\": \"C:\\\\GitHub\\\\Berreman\\\\specs\\\\0026\\\\.feature-list-md\", \"old_string\": \"  *Experiment* (groups, collections, detectors), and *Settings*\\n  (lan...\n[tool Read] {\"file_path\": \"C:\\\\GitHub\\\\Berreman\\\\specs\\\\0026\\\\.feature-list-md\", \"offset\": 516, \"limit\": 90}\n[tool Edit] {\"replace_all\": false, \"file_path\": \"C:\\\\GitHub\\\\Berreman\\\\specs\\\\0026\\\\.feature-list-md\", \"old_string\": \"## Open questions and naming to confirm\\n\\nThese are the points this do...\nNow the glossary — update D, R-axis definitions, ray-group count, and add the new geometry terms.\n[tool Edit] {\"replace_all\": false, \"file_path\": \"C:\\\\GitHub\\\\Berreman\\\\specs\\\\0026\\\\.feature-list-md\", \"old_string\": \"- **OT — Optical Table.** The top-down working surface.\\n- **OE — Optic...\nLet me verify cross-references are still correct after the edits.\n[tool Grep] {\"pattern\": \"see §|§\\\\d+\", \"path\": \"C:\\\\GitHub\\\\Berreman\\\\specs\\\\0026\\\\.feature-list-md\", \"output_mode\": \"content\", \"-n\": true}\nLine 429 references local help as §12, but local help is §13. Fixing that stale cross-reference.\n[tool Read] {\"file_path\": \"C:\\\\GitHub\\\\Berreman\\\\specs\\\\0026\\\\.feature-list-md\", \"offset\": 427, \"limit\": 4}\n[tool Edit] {\"replace_all\": false, \"file_path\": \"C:\\\\GitHub\\\\Berreman\\\\specs\\\\0026\\\\.feature-list-md\", \"old_string\": \"  and what its controls do. *Keep; see §12.*\", \"new_string\": \"  and wha...\n[tool Grep] {\"pattern\": \"four|PD|[Pp]hoto|analyzer\", \"path\": \"C:\\\\GitHub\\\\Berreman\\\\specs\\\\0026\\\\.feature-list-md\", \"output_mode\": \"content\", \"-n\": true}\nLine 347 still says \"four side rays\" — updating to eight for consistency.\n[tool Read] {\"file_path\": \"C:\\\\GitHub\\\\Berreman\\\\specs\\\\0026\\\\.feature-list-md\", \"offset\": 340, \"limit\": 12}\n[tool Edit] {\"replace_all\": false, \"file_path\": \"C:\\\\GitHub\\\\Berreman\\\\specs\\\\0026\\\\.feature-list-md\", \"old_string\": \"element is, how the four side rays are offset, how reflection is drawn\"...\nThe document is consistent. Now let me append the history entry via the safe writer. First I'll write the one-line summary to an allowed location (`.artifacts`, since the prior cycle's escalation showed `Temp/` is out of scope).\n[tool Write] {\"file_path\": \"C:\\\\GitHub\\\\Berreman\\\\specs\\\\0026\\\\.artifacts\\\\0026-feature-list-summary.txt\", \"content\": \"Updated Optical Constructor feature list with operator answers: added e...\n[tool Bash] {\"command\": \"cd \\\"C:\\\\GitHub\\\\Berreman\\\" && python -m ai_strategy_generator.spec_writer.history_cli append \\\\\\n    --spec-folder \\\"C:\\\\GitHub\\\\Berreman\\\\specs\\\\0026\\\" \\\\\\n    --...\nThe installed CLI doesn't accept `feature-list` as an intent (the prior agent decision row used `spec`, and the schema offers `spec`/`claim-check`/`gates`/`handoff`). I'll use `spec` to match the existing agent-decision convention.\n[tool Bash] {\"command\": \"cd \\\"C:\\\\GitHub\\\\Berreman\\\" && python -m ai_strategy_generator.spec_writer.history_cli append \\\\\\n    --spec-folder \\\"C:\\\\GitHub\\\\Berreman\\\\specs\\\\0026\\\" \\\\\\n    --...\n[tool Bash] {\"command\": \"cd \\\"C:\\\\GitHub\\\\Berreman\\\\specs\\\\0026\\\" && tail -n 1 .history\", \"description\": \"Verify last history line\"}\nI've updated the feature list to fold in the operator's answers and appended the decision to `.history`. Summary of what changed in `.feature-list-md`:\n\n**New geometric model (§7, retitled \"Optical elements: geometry, drawer, and rotations\")**\n- **§7.1 Bounding box + two normals** — every element is a bounding box with N1 (primary/face normal) and N2 (secondary). Unrotated, N1 lies along the CR (and R1), N2 along the table normal. `A × A × B` proportions by role: optical elements thin-and-wide, light source long-and-narrow, detector like an optical element.\n- **§7.2 The drawer** — a function of placement point + 3 rotations. First build uses one standard **cylinder drawer**: visible frame, very light-grey transparent interior (so rays show through), darker source, near-black detector with visible frame, plus a **show/hide bounding-box** toggle for inspecting rotations.\n- **§7.3 Rotations corrected** — R1 now turns about the **surface normal N1** (coincides with CR only at normal incidence; R2 ≠ 0 decouples it), R2 about the table normal, R3 about the third box axis; noted that the axes follow real optical-fitting mounts and **R3 ≠ 0 breaks R1 ⊥ R2**.\n\n**Other settled answers**\n- **Detector (D)** naming finalized; removed \"photo detector\"/\"PD\" and the analyzer kind — a polarizer is a polarizer wherever placed, any number allowed (§8, §9, glossary, example chain).\n- **Rays (§8)**: one CR + **eight** side rays forming a 45° circle at normal incidence, with a **show-CR-only / show-all** toggle; weights left to the spec-author (web check confirmed only chief/marginal-ray vocabulary, no canonical pixel weights).\n- **Controls (§6, §10)**: **Ctrl+wheel = zoom**, **Ctrl+Shift+wheel = R2**.\n- **Optical table (§6)**: grey plate, default **1.2 m × 2 m × 10 cm**, resizable.\n- **Element identity (§9)**: reserve an **id slot** in the schema and an element-menu action that opens an empty modal placeholder now (real device/material picker deferred).\n- **Storage (§11)**: groups and collections in a **separate JSON**.\n- **Sequencing**: added the operator's \"build the constructor first\" priority; ribbon tab set accepted as a starting point.\n- Rewrote the open-questions section into \"settled decisions\" + a short list of genuine spec-author details, and updated the glossary. Also fixed a stale §12→§13 cross-reference.\n\nOne deviation to flag: the prompt specified `--intent feature-list` for the history writer, but the installed `history_cli` only accepts `spec/claim-check/gates/handoff`, so I used `--intent spec` (matching the prior agent-decision row). No files outside scope (`.feature-list-md`, `.history`, `.artifacts/`) were touched.\nI've updated the feature list to fold in the operator's answers and appended the decision to `.history`. Summary of what changed in `.feature-list-md`:\n\n**New geometric model (§7, retitled \"Optical elements: geometry, drawer, and rotations\")**\n- **§7.1 Bounding box + two normals** — every element is a bounding box with N1 (primary/face normal) and N2 (secondary). Unrotated, N1 lies along the CR (and R1), N2 along the table normal. `A × A × B` proportions by role: optical elements thin-and-wide, light source long-and-narrow, detector like an optical element.\n- **§7.2 The drawer** — a function of placement point + 3 rotations. First build uses one standard **cylinder drawer**: visible frame, very light-grey transparent interior (so rays show through), darker source, near-black detector with visible frame, plus a **show/hide bounding-box** toggle for inspecting rotations.\n- **§7.3 Rotations corrected** — R1 now turns about the **surface normal N1** (coincides with CR only at normal incidence; R2 ≠ 0 decouples it), R2 about the table normal, R3 about the third box axis; noted that the axes follow real optical-fitting mounts and **R3 ≠ 0 breaks R1 ⊥ R2**.\n\n**Other settled answers**\n- **Detector (D)** naming finalized; removed \"photo detector\"/\"PD\" and the analyzer kind — a polarizer is a polarizer wherever placed, any number allowed (§8, §9, glossary, example chain).\n- **Rays (§8)**: one CR + **eight** side rays forming a 45° circle at normal incidence, with a **show-CR-only / show-all** toggle; weights left to the spec-author (web check confirmed only chief/marginal-ray vocabulary, no canonical pixel weights).\n- **Controls (§6, §10)**: **Ctrl+wheel = zoom**, **Ctrl+Shift+wheel = R2**.\n- **Optical table (§6)**: grey plate, default **1.2 m × 2 m × 10 cm**, resizable.\n- **Element identity (§9)**: reserve an **id slot** in the schema and an element-menu action that opens an empty modal placeholder now (real device/material picker deferred).\n- **Storage (§11)**: groups and collections in a **separate JSON**.\n- **Sequencing**: added the operator's \"build the constructor first\" priority; ribbon tab set accepted as a starting point.\n- Rewrote the open-questions section into \"settled decisions\" + a short list of genuine spec-author details, and updated the glossary. Also fixed a stale §12→§13 cross-reference.\n\nOne deviation to flag: the prompt specified `--intent feature-list` for the history writer, but the installed `history_cli` only accepts `spec/claim-check/gates/handoff`, so I used `--intent spec` (matching the prior agent-decision row). No files outside scope (`.feature-list-md`, `.history`, `.artifacts/`) were touched."}
{"at": "2026-06-05T22:04:24Z", "commit_ref": "84cc050", "intent": "feature-list", "actor": "user", "kind": "input", "content": "Here are the comments:\nAll keys and duplicate mouse commands (where applicable) must be in one centralized locations. Since this is F#, then we model the command using DUs and then assemble one or two variants using a 3 state DU (KB only, mouse only, KB + mouse – or something like that – that will be a design decision, here we just make some small notes).\n`For a polarizer R1 is its azimuth.` - I think that this is wrong. R1 is a normal to the face but azimuth is on the face. R2 is the azimuth at (0, 0, 0)\n\n`Showing and editing the angles.` - The user does not edit angles one by one. All that happens when a local element menu is shown.\n\n`Placement point and snapping` PP snaps to CR. Changing R2 and / or R3 will change the direction of R and may change the direction of T. Anything that is snapped to the ray(s) after the element that is being rotated must travel with the ray(s) and all the distances are preserved. The placement point can be edited at the same local element menu where the angles are. Basically everything that we do with the element can be done via that menu. \n\nLight source and the detector have default placement locations: Light source near the left side of the table in the middle and detector is near the right side of the table in the middle. The distances are measured from the beginning of the CR originating at the light source and terminates at the detector. The initial distance between them is 2 meters. Moving the light source drags everything with it due to snapping. The light source must have a position reset (via its menu). The rest will just re-snap.\n\nChanging the tracked ray (e.g. from T to R) or removing the ray when both are used makes the elements on the way of removed ray orphaned. This is the only way to have orphaned elements. If the ray is restored, then they re-snap (if the ray passes within some configured distance from PP). Otherwise, the elements stay orphaned.\n\nWhen an element is placed on a ray that is not horizontal then R2 is always measured from the ray direction. That means that if an element is on a horizontal ray with some R2 and then is placed on a non-horizontal ray with some r2, then in table system of coordinates the element has (r2 + R2) angle of rotation. \n\nSHIFT + LEFT-PRESS + DRAG – only drags the element within the boundaries of two elements that are on both sides of the current element. Once the element is dropped the table is redrawn as the rays may change. Shift left / right do the same.\nCTL + LEFT-PRESS + DRAG element allows dragging the elements between different rays. Once the element is dropped the table is redrawn as the rays may change.\n\nEditing: drag elements from the ribbon to the table. The elements snap to the middle of the closest CR path when the element is dropped (mouse released).\n\nElement group refinement. The purpose of the element group is to simplify the process making similar experiments out of the same setup. For example, we want to swap LP and CP without getting into a complicated process of adding LP, specifying its fine details, and then removing it by placing a CP and specifying its details and then back. The elements in the group may go either into same way (only one is allowed) OR zero, one, or more could be placed at the same time. So a group allows describing all elements in it and that easy swapping without losing the information about the element, which would be the case with simple delete / add.\n\nUpdate the feature list."}
{"at": "2026-06-05T22:04:24Z", "commit_ref": "84cc050", "intent": "spec", "actor": "agent", "kind": "decision", "content": "Folded operator comments into the Optical Constructor feature list: corrected that R1 is not a polarizer's azimuth (R1 axis is the face normal; azimuth lies in the face; at rest pose R2 gives the azimuth); made element editing menu-centric (all angles/PP edited from one local element menu, not inline one-by-one); expanded placement/snapping so changing R2/R3 re-aims R/T and everything snapped downstream travels with the rays preserving distances; added default LS (left-middle) and detector (right-middle) positions 2 m apart along the CR, moving LS drags the chain, LS has a position reset; added orphaned-element rule (only switching the tracked ray or removing one of two in-use rays orphans elements; re-snap if the ray returns within a configured distance); added that R2 on a non-horizontal ray is measured from the ray direction so table-frame angle is r2 + R2; redefined drag gestures (Shift+drag slides along the ray bounded by neighbours, Ctrl+drag moves between rays, both redraw on drop) and added ribbon drag-and-drop placement snapping to the nearest CR middle; refined element groups (preserve each member's full configuration for lossless LP/CP swapping; mutually-exclusive vs multi-select members); and noted a centralized command model (F# command DUs with a KB/mouse/both binding). Updated settled-decisions list and glossary.\n"}
{"at": "2026-06-05T22:09:25Z", "commit_ref": "84cc050", "intent": "feature-list", "actor": "user", "kind": "output", "content": "[tool Edit] {\"replace_all\": false, \"file_path\": \"C:\\\\GitHub\\\\Berreman\\\\specs\\\\0026\\\\.feature-list-md\", \"old_string\": \"operation orphans elements — ordinary rotation and dragging always keep...\nNow update §10 interaction model — refine Shift+drag and add Ctrl+drag:\n[tool Edit] {\"replace_all\": false, \"file_path\": \"C:\\\\GitHub\\\\Berreman\\\\specs\\\\0026\\\\.feature-list-md\", \"old_string\": \"- **Shift + left-press + drag** → move the placement point **along the\\...\nNow add the centralized-command note to §10. Let me also check the §10 intro mentions \"advice on each item\":\n[tool Edit] {\"replace_all\": false, \"file_path\": \"C:\\\\GitHub\\\\Berreman\\\\specs\\\\0026\\\\.feature-list-md\", \"old_string\": \"**Non-functional notes.** A consistent, discoverable scheme matters mor...\nNow refine §11 element groups with the operator's purpose clarification:\n[tool Edit] {\"replace_all\": false, \"file_path\": \"C:\\\\GitHub\\\\Berreman\\\\specs\\\\0026\\\\.feature-list-md\", \"old_string\": \"The capability is to **turn the elements of each group on and off\\nquic...\nLet me update the \"Decisions settled\" R1 bullet and add a glossary entry for orphaned elements. Let me read the relevant glossary tail region:\n[tool Read] {\"file_path\": \"C:\\\\GitHub\\\\Berreman\\\\specs\\\\0026\\\\.feature-list-md\", \"offset\": 600, \"limit\": 60}\n[tool Read] {\"file_path\": \"C:\\\\GitHub\\\\Berreman\\\\specs\\\\0026\\\\.feature-list-md\", \"offset\": 658, \"limit\": 90}\n[tool Edit] {\"replace_all\": false, \"file_path\": \"C:\\\\GitHub\\\\Berreman\\\\specs\\\\0026\\\\.feature-list-md\", \"old_string\": \"- **R1 axis.** Settled: **R1 turns around the element's surface normal\\...\nNow add glossary entries for the local element menu and orphaned elements:\n[tool Edit] {\"replace_all\": false, \"file_path\": \"C:\\\\GitHub\\\\Berreman\\\\specs\\\\0026\\\\.feature-list-md\", \"old_string\": \"- **PP — Placement Point.** The point that snaps an element onto the CR...\n[tool Edit] {\"replace_all\": false, \"file_path\": \"C:\\\\GitHub\\\\Berreman\\\\specs\\\\0026\\\\.feature-list-md\", \"old_string\": \"- **Storage of groups and collections.** Settled: a **separate JSON\\n  ...\nLet me soften one normative \"must\" I introduced in §8 to keep the prose free of contract grammar:\n[tool Edit] {\"replace_all\": false, \"file_path\": \"C:\\\\GitHub\\\\Berreman\\\\specs\\\\0026\\\\.feature-list-md\", \"old_string\": \"direction of the transmitted ray T, and anything snapped to a ray after...\nNow let me append the decision to `.history` via the safe writer. First write the one-line summary to an allowed location (`.artifacts/`):\n[tool Write] {\"file_path\": \"C:\\\\GitHub\\\\Berreman\\\\specs\\\\0026\\\\.artifacts\\\\0026-feature-list-summary.txt\", \"content\": \"Folded operator comments into the Optical Constructor feature list: cor...\n[tool Read] {\"file_path\": \"C:\\\\GitHub\\\\Berreman\\\\specs\\\\0026\\\\.artifacts\\\\0026-feature-list-summary.txt\"}\n[tool Write] {\"file_path\": \"C:\\\\GitHub\\\\Berreman\\\\specs\\\\0026\\\\.artifacts\\\\0026-feature-list-summary.txt\", \"content\": \"Folded operator comments into the Optical Constructor feature list: cor...\n[tool Bash] {\"command\": \"cd \\\"C:\\\\GitHub\\\\Berreman\\\" && python -m ai_strategy_generator.spec_writer.history_cli append --spec-folder \\\"C:\\\\GitHub\\\\Berreman\\\\specs\\\\0026\\\" --at \\\"2026-06-05T...\nThe installed CLI doesn't accept `feature-list` as an intent (same as the prior cycle). I'll use `spec` to match the existing agent-decision convention:\n[tool Bash] {\"command\": \"cd \\\"C:\\\\GitHub\\\\Berreman\\\" && python -m ai_strategy_generator.spec_writer.history_cli append --spec-folder \\\"C:\\\\GitHub\\\\Berreman\\\\specs\\\\0026\\\" --at \\\"2026-06-05T...\n[tool Bash] {\"command\": \"cd \\\"C:\\\\GitHub\\\\Berreman\\\\specs\\\\0026\\\" && powershell -NoProfile -Command \\\"Get-Content .history -Tail 1\\\"\", \"description\": \"Verify last history line\"}\nI've folded the operator's comments into `.feature-list-md` and appended the decision to `.history`. Here's what changed.\n\n**§7.3 — rotations**\n- **R1 ≠ azimuth (correction).** Removed \"For a polarizer R1 is its azimuth.\" and replaced it with the operator's correction: R1's axis is the *face normal*; a polarizer's azimuth lies *in* the face; at the rest pose (0,0,0) it is **R2** that gives the azimuth.\n- **Editing is menu-centric.** The user no longer edits angles one-by-one inline — all editing (exact angles, resets, per-rotation lock/unlock, and the placement point) happens in the **one local element menu**, which exposes everything the user can do to the element.\n- **R2 on non-horizontal rays.** Added that R2 is measured from the *incident ray direction*, so an element moved onto a ray tilted by r2 ends up at **(r2 + R2)** in the table frame.\n\n**§8 — ray model**\n- **Placement/snapping** rewritten: PP snaps to the CR; changing R2/R3 re-aims R (and may re-aim T); everything snapped downstream travels with the rays with all distances preserved; PP is edited from the same local menu.\n- **Default positions:** LS at left-middle, detector at right-middle, **2 m apart** along the CR; moving the LS drags the chain; LS has a **position reset**; the rest re-snap.\n- **Orphaned elements:** new rule — only switching the tracked ray or removing one of two in-use rays orphans elements; they re-snap if the ray returns within a configured distance of the PP, else stay orphaned.\n- **Ribbon drag-and-drop:** adding an element is a drag from the ribbon, snapping to the middle of the closest CR path on drop.\n\n**§10 — interaction**\n- **Shift+drag** redefined to slide an element along its ray bounded by its two neighbours; **Ctrl+drag** moves it to a different ray; both redraw on drop.\n- **Centralized commands:** added a note that keys and their duplicate mouse commands live in one place, modelled in F# as command DUs carrying a keyboard/mouse/both binding (recorded as direction, not prescription).\n\n**§11 — element groups**\n- Added the purpose (lossless LP↔CP-style swapping that preserves each member's full configuration) and the two member modes: **mutually exclusive** (at most one in the beam) vs **multi-select** (zero/one/several).\n\nAlso updated the settled-decisions list and glossary (added *local element menu* and *orphaned element*).\n\nTwo notes:\n- Kept the document prose-first and free of RFC-2119 acceptance grammar (softened one stray \"must\" to \"travels\").\n- As in the prior cycle, the installed `history_cli` rejects `--intent feature-list` (only `spec/claim-check/gates/handoff`), so I used `--intent spec` to match the existing agent-decision row. Only `.feature-list-md`, `.history`, and `.artifacts/` were touched.\nI've folded the operator's comments into `.feature-list-md` and appended the decision to `.history`. Here's what changed.\n\n**§7.3 — rotations**\n- **R1 ≠ azimuth (correction).** Removed \"For a polarizer R1 is its azimuth.\" and replaced it with the operator's correction: R1's axis is the *face normal*; a polarizer's azimuth lies *in* the face; at the rest pose (0,0,0) it is **R2** that gives the azimuth.\n- **Editing is menu-centric.** The user no longer edits angles one-by-one inline — all editing (exact angles, resets, per-rotation lock/unlock, and the placement point) happens in the **one local element menu**, which exposes everything the user can do to the element.\n- **R2 on non-horizontal rays.** Added that R2 is measured from the *incident ray direction*, so an element moved onto a ray tilted by r2 ends up at **(r2 + R2)** in the table frame.\n\n**§8 — ray model**\n- **Placement/snapping** rewritten: PP snaps to the CR; changing R2/R3 re-aims R (and may re-aim T); everything snapped downstream travels with the rays with all distances preserved; PP is edited from the same local menu.\n- **Default positions:** LS at left-middle, detector at right-middle, **2 m apart** along the CR; moving the LS drags the chain; LS has a **position reset**; the rest re-snap.\n- **Orphaned elements:** new rule — only switching the tracked ray or removing one of two in-use rays orphans elements; they re-snap if the ray returns within a configured distance of the PP, else stay orphaned.\n- **Ribbon drag-and-drop:** adding an element is a drag from the ribbon, snapping to the middle of the closest CR path on drop.\n\n**§10 — interaction**\n- **Shift+drag** redefined to slide an element along its ray bounded by its two neighbours; **Ctrl+drag** moves it to a different ray; both redraw on drop.\n- **Centralized commands:** added a note that keys and their duplicate mouse commands live in one place, modelled in F# as command DUs carrying a keyboard/mouse/both binding (recorded as direction, not prescription).\n\n**§11 — element groups**\n- Added the purpose (lossless LP↔CP-style swapping that preserves each member's full configuration) and the two member modes: **mutually exclusive** (at most one in the beam) vs **multi-select** (zero/one/several).\n\nAlso updated the settled-decisions list and glossary (added *local element menu* and *orphaned element*).\n\nTwo notes:\n- Kept the document prose-first and free of RFC-2119 acceptance grammar (softened one stray \"must\" to \"travels\").\n- As in the prior cycle, the installed `history_cli` rejects `--intent feature-list` (only `spec/claim-check/gates/handoff`), so I used `--intent spec` to match the existing agent-decision row. Only `.feature-list-md`, `.history`, and `.artifacts/` were touched."}
{"at": "2026-06-05T23:18:18Z", "commit_ref": "84cc050", "intent": "feature-list", "actor": "user", "kind": "input", "content": "Here are the comments:\nCRITICAL\nClear up the documents from all discussions / how we got to decisions. Make it authoritative source of information. When mouse and keyboard provide the same functionality, then combine the controls together to make it clear.\nMake it explicit that the drawer gets the element kind AND the element value id (currently will be modeled as None in F#). That will allow customizing the look later without rewiring a lot of things.\nReview the structure to ensure that the document consistent.\n\nSMALL COMMENT\nPP is the center of the rectangular bounding box."}
{"at": "2026-06-05T23:18:18Z", "commit_ref": "84cc050", "intent": "spec", "actor": "agent", "kind": "decision", "content": "Made the feature list an authoritative source: removed the retrospective \"Decisions settled / how we got here\" section and the operator-settled/accepted/proposed/annotated discussion artifacts throughout (intro, sequencing, ribbon set, detector/analyzer, group storage, reset), leaving a forward-looking \"Details left to the spec-author\" only; reorganised the interaction model (S10) by command so mouse and keyboard bindings that do the same thing are combined on one line (open dialog, reset rotation, delete, duplicate, local help, slide-along-ray, reset view, zoom); made the drawer take the element kind AND the element value id (absent / None in F#) so per-device/material looks can be added later without rewiring, tied to the S9 element value id slot; stated PP is the centre of the element's rectangular bounding box; updated glossary (Drawer, PP, new Element value id entry).\n"}
{"at": "2026-06-05T23:23:37Z", "commit_ref": "84cc050", "intent": "feature-list", "actor": "user", "kind": "output", "content": "[tool Edit] {\"replace_all\": false, \"file_path\": \"C:\\\\GitHub\\\\Berreman\\\\specs\\\\0026\\\\.feature-list-md\", \"old_string\": \"- **PP — Placement Point.** The point that snaps an element onto the CR...\nLet me add a glossary entry for the element value id for consistency:\n[tool Edit] {\"replace_all\": false, \"file_path\": \"C:\\\\GitHub\\\\Berreman\\\\specs\\\\0026\\\\.feature-list-md\", \"old_string\": \"- **LP / CP — Linear / Circular Polarizer.** A polarizer regardless of\\...\nNow let me scan for remaining discussion/meta-commentary artifacts to ensure the document reads as authoritative:\n[tool Grep] {\"pattern\": \"operator|Settled|Resolved|Proposed|proposed|annotated|advice|Keep\\\\.|accepted|settled|Corrected|Refined\", \"path\": \"C:\\\\GitHub\\\\Berreman\\\\specs\\\\0026\\\\.feature-list-...\nLet me refine a few remaining tentative phrasings. First the intro:\n[tool Edit] {\"replace_all\": false, \"file_path\": \"C:\\\\GitHub\\\\Berreman\\\\specs\\\\0026\\\\.feature-list-md\", \"old_string\": \"prose*, not the structured spec: it captures who needs what and why,\\nt...\n[tool Read] {\"file_path\": \"C:\\\\GitHub\\\\Berreman\\\\specs\\\\0026\\\\.feature-list-md\", \"offset\": 303, \"limit\": 5}\n[tool Edit] {\"replace_all\": false, \"file_path\": \"C:\\\\GitHub\\\\Berreman\\\\specs\\\\0026\\\\.feature-list-md\", \"old_string\": \"**Reset.** A single action (proposed **Shift+R, with confirmation**)\\n*...\n[tool Edit] {\"replace_all\": false, \"file_path\": \"C:\\\\GitHub\\\\Berreman\\\\specs\\\\0026\\\\.feature-list-md\", \"old_string\": \"The proposed standard names (to be reviewed and completed):\", \"new_stri...\n[tool Read] {\"file_path\": \"C:\\\\GitHub\\\\Berreman\\\\specs\\\\0026\\\\.feature-list-md\", \"offset\": 662, \"limit\": 8}\n[tool Edit] {\"replace_all\": false, \"file_path\": \"C:\\\\GitHub\\\\Berreman\\\\specs\\\\0026\\\\.feature-list-md\", \"old_string\": \"should either be undoable or ask for confirmation, consistent with the\\...\nLet me re-read the new §10 to verify coherence:\n[tool Read] {\"file_path\": \"C:\\\\GitHub\\\\Berreman\\\\specs\\\\0026\\\\.feature-list-md\", \"offset\": 470, \"limit\": 120}\nThe §10 rewrite reads well. Let me verify section numbering and headings are consistent:\n[tool Grep] {\"pattern\": \"^## |^### \", \"path\": \"C:\\\\GitHub\\\\Berreman\\\\specs\\\\0026\\\\.feature-list-md\", \"output_mode\": \"content\", \"-n\": true}\nThe document is consistent (sections 1–14 sequential, glossary updated, cross-references intact). Now let me append the history entry via the safe writer. First I'll write the summary to a temp UTF-8 file:\n[tool Write] {\"file_path\": \"C:\\\\GitHub\\\\Berreman\\\\specs\\\\0026\\\\.artifacts\\\\feature-list-summary-0026.txt\", \"content\": \"Made the feature list an authoritative source: removed the retrospectiv...\n[tool Bash] {\"command\": \"python -m ai_strategy_generator.spec_writer.history_cli append \\\\\\n  --spec-folder \\\"C:\\\\GitHub\\\\Berreman\\\\specs\\\\0026\\\" \\\\\\n  --at \\\"2026-06-05T23:18:18Z\\\" \\\\\\n  -...\nThe CLI version doesn't accept `feature-list` as intent; the prior agent decision line in this bundle used `spec`. I'll match that precedent:\n[tool Bash] {\"command\": \"python -m ai_strategy_generator.spec_writer.history_cli append \\\\\\n  --spec-folder \\\"C:\\\\GitHub\\\\Berreman\\\\specs\\\\0026\\\" \\\\\\n  --at \\\"2026-06-05T23:18:18Z\\\" \\\\\\n  -...\nThe history line was appended (1019 bytes written). Let me verify it landed correctly:\n[tool Bash] {\"command\": \"python -c \\\"\\nimport json\\nwith open('specs/0026/.history','r',encoding='utf-8') as f:\\n    lines=f.readlines()\\no=json.loads(lines[-1])\\nprint('lines now:', len(li...\nThe work is complete. Here's a summary of what I did.\n\n## Changes to `specs/0026/.feature-list-md`\n\nActing on the CRITICAL and SMALL comments, I made the feature list an **authoritative source** rather than a record of discussions:\n\n**1. Cleared out \"how we got to decisions\" / discussion artifacts**\n- Removed the retrospective **\"Decisions settled\"** section entirely (it only restated what the body already says), replacing it with a forward-looking **\"Details left to the spec-author\"** section for the genuine lower-level refinements.\n- Stripped the \"the operator settled / accepted / proposed\", \"*Keep.*\", \"*New*\", \"*Refined*\", \"*Resolved*\", \"annotated\" meta-commentary throughout — intro, Sequencing, ribbon tab set (§1), detector/analyzer naming (§8, §9), group storage (§11), reset (§7.3), undo/safety (§14) — so each now states the decision as fact.\n- Reframed the intro to call the document the authoritative description.\n\n**2. Combined mouse + keyboard controls (§10 rewritten)**\n- Reorganized the interaction model **by command instead of by device**, so commands reachable both ways are on one line: open dialog (double-click / right-click), reset rotation (Shift+R / right-click), delete, duplicate, local help (F1 / right-click), slide-along-ray (Shift+drag / arrow keys), reset view (Ctrl+0 / button), zoom (wheel / Ctrl+wheel). Grouped into Active-element / Rotations / Move / Table & view / Global, plus the centralized-command note.\n\n**3. Drawer gets element kind AND value id (§7.2, §9, glossary)**\n- The drawer now takes placement point, three rotations, **element kind, and element value id** (absent / `None` in F# for the first build), tied to the §9 value-id schema slot, so per-device/material looks can be added later without rewiring placement/ray logic.\n\n**4. Small comment**\n- Stated **PP is the centre of the element's rectangular bounding box** (§8 and glossary).\n\n**5. Consistency pass** — verified sections 1–14 are sequential, cross-references resolve, and updated the glossary (Drawer, PP, new \"Element value id\" entry). No RFC-2119 grammar, AC blocks, or files-in-scope lists introduced.\n\n## History\nAppended one `decision` line via the safe writer (`history_cli`). Note: the CLI in this repo rejects `--intent feature-list` (accepts only `spec`/`claim-check`/`gates`/`handoff`), so I used `--intent spec` to match the precedent set by the prior agent decision line in this bundle.\n\nEdits stayed within the allowed scope (`.feature-list-md`, `.history`, and the `.artifacts` temp summary file).\nThe work is complete. Here's a summary of what I did.\n\n## Changes to `specs/0026/.feature-list-md`\n\nActing on the CRITICAL and SMALL comments, I made the feature list an **authoritative source** rather than a record of discussions:\n\n**1. Cleared out \"how we got to decisions\" / discussion artifacts**\n- Removed the retrospective **\"Decisions settled\"** section entirely (it only restated what the body already says), replacing it with a forward-looking **\"Details left to the spec-author\"** section for the genuine lower-level refinements.\n- Stripped the \"the operator settled / accepted / proposed\", \"*Keep.*\", \"*New*\", \"*Refined*\", \"*Resolved*\", \"annotated\" meta-commentary throughout — intro, Sequencing, ribbon tab set (§1), detector/analyzer naming (§8, §9), group storage (§11), reset (§7.3), undo/safety (§14) — so each now states the decision as fact.\n- Reframed the intro to call the document the authoritative description.\n\n**2. Combined mouse + keyboard controls (§10 rewritten)**\n- Reorganized the interaction model **by command instead of by device**, so commands reachable both ways are on one line: open dialog (double-click / right-click), reset rotation (Shift+R / right-click), delete, duplicate, local help (F1 / right-click), slide-along-ray (Shift+drag / arrow keys), reset view (Ctrl+0 / button), zoom (wheel / Ctrl+wheel). Grouped into Active-element / Rotations / Move / Table & view / Global, plus the centralized-command note.\n\n**3. Drawer gets element kind AND value id (§7.2, §9, glossary)**\n- The drawer now takes placement point, three rotations, **element kind, and element value id** (absent / `None` in F# for the first build), tied to the §9 value-id schema slot, so per-device/material looks can be added later without rewiring placement/ray logic.\n\n**4. Small comment**\n- Stated **PP is the centre of the element's rectangular bounding box** (§8 and glossary).\n\n**5. Consistency pass** — verified sections 1–14 are sequential, cross-references resolve, and updated the glossary (Drawer, PP, new \"Element value id\" entry). No RFC-2119 grammar, AC blocks, or files-in-scope lists introduced.\n\n## History\nAppended one `decision` line via the safe writer (`history_cli`). Note: the CLI in this repo rejects `--intent feature-list` (accepts only `spec`/`claim-check`/`gates`/`handoff`), so I used `--intent spec` to match the precedent set by the prior agent decision line in this bundle.\n\nEdits stayed within the allowed scope (`.feature-list-md`, `.history`, and the `.artifacts` temp summary file)."}
{"at": "2026-06-05T23:43:28Z", "commit_ref": "84cc050", "intent": "spec", "actor": "user", "kind": "input", "content": "Examine the existing codebase, look up the web for the best practices / recommended UI parameters asked in `Details left to the spec-author`, then write the spec based on the feature list."}
{"at": "2026-06-05T23:43:28Z", "commit_ref": "84cc050", "intent": "spec", "actor": "agent", "kind": "output", "content": "Authored the structured .spec-md for Spec 0026 (Optical Constructor UI) from the finalized feature list, after examining the existing OpticalConstructor F#/Avalonia+FuncUI codebase and researching optics ray-diagram drawing conventions. Structure: Part 0 binding constraints (reuse engine/units/storage, canonical SI, pure MVU, public FuncUI surface only with the audit-gated clone unreferenced, single-source-of-commands twice, schematic n=1/1.5, plausible-expansion exclusions, net-new vs reused inventory); Part A (CRITICAL) element geometry/placement/rotation domain model (new Placement.fs: bounding box + N1/N2 normals, PP = box centre, R1/R2/R3 with R2-measured-from-incident-ray r2+R2 law and R3 non-orthogonality, per-axis locks with R3 default-locked, CatalogueKind->ConstructorElement mapping with LP/CP both ->Polarizer and Analyzer left untouched, value-id None slot, R/T emission smart constructor, schema+Project extensions); Part B (CRITICAL) ray model in new RayModel.fs (CR+8 side rays on 45-deg circle, bundle radius 0.4*face/2, IRG/RRG/TRG + detector terminates, snapping with distance-preserving downstream travel, default LS/D 2 m apart + LS position reset, orphaning rules, Snell schematic tracing); Part C optical table + top-down surface (new Table.fs/Drawer.fs/ConstructorTable.fs: grey plate 1.2x2.0x0.10 m resizable+stored, pan/zoom/rotate/reset view, table-selection, one cylinder drawer taking kind+value id with darker source / near-black detector / show-hide bbox, concrete drawing weights from research, active-element >=2px >=3:1 indicator, CR-only/all toggle); Part D ribbon-and-menu shell (new Ribbon.fs: Build/Element/Trace-View/Experiment/Settings tabs from the command registry, collapsible ribbon<->menus single-sourced, appended contextual element tab, EN/RU flex layout, Legacy menu entry to the existing dockable screen, constructor as default landing extending Shell.Page); Part E interaction model (new Commands.fs centralized command DU with 3-state KB/mouse/both binding feeding ribbon+menus+input; active-element/rotation/move/table/global command tables; shift-drag bounded slide, ctrl-drag reassign, inert plain drag + hint, drag-from-ribbon placement, configurable key map persisted); Part F catalogue + value-id placeholder empty modal (real picker out of scope); Part G groups (member modes mutually-exclusive/multi-select, lossless swap, multiple detectors + primary, separate app-data groups/collections JSON via new GroupsLibrary.fs + schema); Part H experiment collections; Part I EN/RU localization (new Localization.fs + strings.json runtime-read/editable, language persisted in EnvironmentSettings, startup completeness check with English fallback + copyable error in Program.fs, language-neutral scientific symbols); Part J standardized controls (new Controls.fs flavours, consolidating positiveCta/negativeCta); Part K undo/redo participation reusing History.EditHistory multi-level + safety confirmations. Added Operator-facing UX commitments section covering all six checklist points (with the spec-writer hidden-controls checklist marked N/A for a desktop Avalonia app) and full Acceptance criteria / Files in scope / Test artifacts / References sections. All cited code pointers were Read-verified before committing (BeamTree.fs, Project.fs, Units.fs, History.fs, Schematic.fs, Shell.fs, UserEnvironment.fs, AppShell.fs, ConstructionView.fs, ProjectFile.fs, SchemaValidation.fs, project schema); localization absence confirmed by grep. Edits limited to .spec-md, .history, and .artifacts.\n"}
